## Enforcement

### Linting Rules
Consider adding ESLint rules to detect:
- Global mutable exports
- Module-level mutable variables
- Singleton patterns with state

### Code Review Guidelines
- Always check for global state usage
- Verify request isolation in server-side code
- Ensure context is passed to all server functions
- Test concurrent request scenarios

### Team Training
- Educate team on Node.js module caching
- Explain security implications of shared state
- Practice identifying problematic patterns
- Regular security reviews of server code

## Related Patterns

### Acceptable Global State
```typescript
// OK - Immutable configuration
export const API_ENDPOINTS = {
  USERS: '/api/users',
  ORDERS: '/api/orders',
} as const;

// OK - Pure functions without state
export function formatCurrency(amount: number): string {
  return `€${amount.toFixed(2)}`;
}

// OK - Read-only caches with proper invalidation
export const configCache = new Map<string, ConfigValue>();
```

### Server-Side Storage Alternatives
- Use databases for persistent data
- Use Redis for session storage
- Use request context for request-scoped data
- Use environment variables for configuration

This rule should be strictly enforced to prevent serious security vulnerabilities and ensure user data privacy and security.
